{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619551"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:32:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:32:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16561"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16561"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.26,0,0.13,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9252"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75721"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9252"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16561"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61239"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7108"},{"type":"tags","id":"7112"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21920"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75721"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cavernous sinus is a paired dural venous sinus located on either side of the sella turcica. It contains several important neurovascular structures and serves as a major venous drainage pathway for the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following dural venous sinuses is the primary drainage pathway of the cavernous sinus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Superior sagittal sinus","Inferior sagittal sinus","Transverse sinus","Straight sinus","Sigmoid sinus"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esigmoid sinus\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary drainage pathway for the cavernous sinus via the superior and inferior petrosal sinuses. The sigmoid sinus then continues as the internal jugular vein in the neck.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior sagittal sinus\u003C/strong\u003E runs in the superior border of the falx cerebri and drains into the transverse sinus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior sagittal sinus\u003C/strong\u003E runs in the inferior border of the falx cerebri and joins the great cerebral vein to form the straight sinus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etransverse sinus\u003C/strong\u003E receives blood from the superior sagittal sinus and straight sinus at the confluence of sinuses\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Estraight sinus\u003C/strong\u003E is formed by the union of the inferior sagittal sinus and great cerebral vein\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cavernous sinus contains several important structures including the internal carotid artery and cranial nerves III, IV, V1, V2 and VI. Understanding its drainage is crucial for recognising the spread of infection in cavernous sinus thrombosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The cavernous sinus drains via the superior and inferior petrosal sinuses into the sigmoid sinus and internal jugular vein.","The cavernous sinus contains important structures including cranial nerves III, IV, V1, V2, and VI, and the internal carotid artery.","Understanding venous drainage patterns is crucial for recognising the spread of infection in cavernous sinus thrombosis."],"references":["Pensak ML. The cavernous sinus: An anatomic study with clinical implication. Laryngoscope Investig Otolaryngol. 2024 Mar 23;9(2):e1226. doi: 10.1002/lio2.1226. PMID: 38525119; PMCID: PMC10960246.","Guo P, Wang WQ. Degree of sigmoid sinus compression and the symptom relief using magnetic resonance angiography in venous pulsating tinnitus. Clin Exp Otorhinolaryngol. 2015 Jun;8(2):111-6. doi: 10.3342/ceo.2015.8.2.111. Epub 2015 May 13. PMID: 26045908; PMCID: PMC4451534.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61239"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16561"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61239"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T20:26:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T20:28:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9252"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75721"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"